{"type":"message","id":"f0b91b56","parentId":"7b579e72","timestamp":"2026-03-27T10:09:16.474Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Planning validation scripts**\n\nI’m considering running a walkforward validation script with the existing detail CSV tied to rule2, even though it focuses on stock analysis rather than sentiment. The user asked about market sentiment factors. It seems beneficial to prepare a plan document for something like \"overlay samples out-of-sample validation,\" but that might only loosely relate. It could be better to create a specific command script or checklist for rule2 validation instead of using the existing overlay script.\n\n**Assessing validation script options**\n\nIt seems there isn't a specific walkforward script for sentiment rule2. I could create a plan document and a shell wrapper for the first validation action, but the instructions say to start the action. Maybe I can develop a checklist to mark current tasks complete and prepare for validation execution, although that wouldn’t actually be a start. Since the user confirmed, I might respond with a message about having created a plan. But I need to ensure we document the progress correctly and not confuse planning with completion.\n\n**Planning next steps in validation**\n\nAfter creating the plan document, I can use the active task CLI to move the current task to completed and promote the next one. Starting the next item could involve searching for a command or launching it directly. To keep things concrete, I might create a shell script with specific commands or document everything in detail. I could also run a lightweight smoke command for overlay walkforward validation using the existing detail CSV. If that completes quickly, that would be great!\n\n**Considering validation approaches**\n\nI’m weighing the options of running a simple command to create a manifest or using an existing script. It might be easier to utilize a Python one-liner to build date splits from the sentiment detail file. I wonder if creating a new report file with the command included would facilitate the first walkforward validation using the existing script. However, I’ll also look into `run_sentiment_threshold_scan.py` to see if it can work with the detail CSV for out-of-sample validation. I could implement a small Python script that splits the validation CSV into train/test by date — that could directly serve the user!\n\n**Planning a holdout split**\n\nI’m thinking about using the existing detail CSV to compute a holdout split, though it would require writing some new code. I might create a script, like `quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/run_rule2_holdout_validation.py`, or place it under the research directory. I should probably check the detail columns first, so I’ll read the first few lines of the CSV to understand its structure. The detail CSV is located in the research/reports root. That could help guide my next steps!","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0a18d76e314b89270169c6570f91ec8198a79b9a66f08c1df0\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpxlcv46Y4jH7u12pve84jVMu7Z3pyrEvkOBQeEQ0sX-6DOjBM1L2mQSELBQ3R1DM9T2Vj06UW3igeC6q3UdbM5Ukax6RP5KO3a8HpWKPKL3NAdYUvx50pT8BB3i_4QXW0VcIMl69HeSsTkaBMdQzyzZ2z0uK1v2MzM5ozYiIgHFY0u6Dn8cwoZ5dxnsfXtifHpdduF4Kv8NmO7VxhIh781y56OHqszAjyDg-95yEAUWIefe_U7t9QPqRCTF8btM0CyunKqVdseOViK1Tcqh_lTkCSSFYZKattqltcQ_1_GoXk3k7na2CdI7n8fGJi1yf6oTdLI9rV3BEWXmWBJJAol-qt1yaI16CYeclWJBigZRTVWvlOitMnZT7OgE4DmnPptekDtCacKYT7LgCQChxFAbHCMV_wYPf7C3UuYbzcdpO3bl0SZdpbjKSo0yRMq0vDdiQR9k_m3kkofDmEHoNH96EA57HTwla9O-TxImGACGMb8l1BJe0kRfKG5i2b20LsUb_Auk65lqU2SMm9QqqkJwxWj5DRJoV5v0v8rZQox6d-dPoJ-0gGjI7zkbcpy1R-q6gVrRdEm8D5tK7IAwdKU1-CnByl3p2k-5O_hk_98ETrKbo87-oNURiAk9VbUzh_UVub5PfwXMtP4aBm0r4T8ykZu7JS8Rw22FNy4DItKhsEg2N9FyUbgeGNj3gcdKzBQ2evOM0BQlwQPeX_ahl-O8fZwNJmYrtzB2d9CvrBslfqUgxFEf8gMANQXHC14axDt2Px-_SIDoHr4YB4hH4qtJjW1ue_HpI_OZ5dMSsRt0eDqtZBeOtNiFC7rT0cKfFdntGi4jKcWKTUu9le2GZXj5CTW