nce hash, using \\\"advance\\\" as a key command. Before committing, I can set the current active task state to active after my update. If I commit after updating, I might have to change ACTIVE_TASK to \\\"done,\\\" which could require another commit. The workspace indicates I should commit changes after edits, so I want to ensure everything is aligned properly in the sequence.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering commit strategy**\\n\\nI think the simplest approach might be to use one commit after reaching a done state by running `git commit`, then getting the hash. After that, I can modify the ACTIVE_TASK to done and commit again, which would give the user a final hash. \\n\\nIf the user didn't actually ask about ACTIVE_TASK, then I need to consider how critical that detail is. However, the developer suggests updating ACTIVE_TASK, so I’ll focus on that. Two commits might be excessive, but I’ll proceed with this plan.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating task progress**\\n\\nI need to ensure I provide the exact hash, which is possible. The acceptance of the new task may not be fully complete, but since the task is active, it should be okay. The user mentioned agreement but might not be expecting everything to be done just yet. Instructions say not to stop after one completed step unless there's a block or user input, so I should at least move to the first commit. \\n\\nI’ll check the git add command for specific files and commit them, then update the active task accordingly.\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"我把“首轮正式验证入口”按真实完成状态推进到提交阶段，然后只提交这轮新增文件。","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a18d76e314b89270169c6578e54dc8198ad83141b5fececd1\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_vDaFqCTL1YDMoXMhGmTX5ku3|fc_0a18d76e314b89270169c6578e8088819884252a202e418203","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 scripts/active_task_cli.py advance --path checklists/ACTIVE_TASK.md --updated '2026-03-27 18:11' --complete-current --p